  "local_port": 37304,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What pre-action would you take in case of earthquakes?",
  "response": "Preparing for an earthquake involves proactive steps to ensure the safety of yourself, your family, and your property. Here are key pre-actions you should consider:\n\n### 1. **Create an Emergency Plan**\n- **Communication Plan:** Establish how your family will communicate if separated. Choose an out-of-area contact person.\n- **Meeting Points:** Designate safe meeting spots both inside and outside your home.\n- **Roles and Responsibilities:** Assign specific tasks to each family member, such as taking care of pets or handling first aid.\n\n### 2. **Assemble an Emergency Kit**\nEnsure your kit includes essentials to last at least 72 hours:\n- **Water:** At least one gallon per person per day.\n- **Non-Perishable Food:** Canned goods, energy bars, and other long-lasting items.\n- **First Aid Supplies:** Bandages, antiseptics, medications, and a first aid manual.\n- **Tools and Supplies:** Flashlights, batteries, a battery-powered radio, multi-tool, and duct tape.\n- **Personal Items:** Prescriptions, glasses, important documents, and clothing.\n- **Miscellaneous:** Sanitation supplies, cash, and copies of important documents.\n\n### 3. **Secure Your Home**\n- **Structural Assessment:** Have a professional inspect your home for earthquake resilience, especially if you live in a high-risk area.\n- **Reinforce Structural Elements:** Strengthen walls, roofs, and foundations as needed.\n- **Secure Heavy Furniture and Appliances:** Use brackets or straps to anchor bookshelves, cabinets, and large appliances to walls.\n- **Fasten Fragile Items:** Secure mirrors, picture frames, and other breakables to prevent injury and damage.\n\n### 4. **Know Safe Spots**\n- **Identify Safe Locations:** Know where to take cover during shaking, such as under sturdy furniture, against an interior wall, or away from windows and heavy objects.\n- **Practice \"Drop, Cover, and Hold On\":** Regularly practice this safety technique with all family members so everyone knows how to react quickly.\n\n### 5. **Stay Informed**\n- **Learn About Local Risks:** Understand the earthquake risk in your area and the potential secondary hazards like tsunamis or landslides.\n- **Sign Up for Alerts:** Enroll in your local emergency notification system to receive real-time updates.\n- **Educate Yourself and Family:** Take first aid and CPR courses, and familiarize yourself with how to shut off utilities like gas, water, and electricity.\n\n### 6. **Prepare Financially**\n- **Insurance Coverage:** Review and update your insurance policies to ensure adequate coverage for earthquake damage.\n- **Emergency Fund:** Set aside money specifically for unexpected expenses related to disasters.\n\n### 7. **Plan for Special Needs**\n- **Consider Vulnerable Family Members:** Make plans for infants, elderly family members, individuals with disabilities, or pets.\n- **Prepare Necessary Supplies:** Ensure you have any required medications, medical devices, or other special items readily available.\n\n### 8. **Stay Involved**\n- **Community Preparedness:** Join or form a local emergency response group or attend community preparedness workshops.\n- **Volunteer:** Get involved in local disaster preparedness and response initiatives to help build a resilient community.\n\nBy taking these pre-action steps, you can significantly increase your preparedness for an earthquake, enhancing your safety and ability to respond effectively when one occurs.",
